Context:
The `noUncheckedIndexedAccess` tsconfig option makes array index access return `T | undefined`. The levenshtein function initializes a full 2D array `dp` but TypeScript doesn't know the indices are safe, so `!` is used 12 times.

Changes for config.ts:
Current code (lines 170-184):
```typescript
const levenshtein = (a: string, b: string): number => {
  const m = a.length;
  const n = b.length;
  const dp: number[][] = Array.from({ length: m + 1 }, (_, i) =>
    Array.from({ length: n + 1 }, (_, j) => (i === 0 ? j : j === 0 ? i : 0)),
  );
  for (let i = 1; i <= m; i++) {
    for (let j = 1; j <= n; j++) {
      dp[i]![j] =
        a[i - 1] === b[j - 1] ? dp[i - 1]![j - 1]! : 1 + Math.min(dp[i - 1]![j]!, dp[i]![j - 1]!, dp[i - 1]![j - 1]!);
    }
  }
  return dp[m]![n]!;
};
```

Recommended approach: Use a flat 1D array with index math to avoid all `!` assertions:
```typescript
const levenshtein = (a: string, b: string): number => {
  const m = a.length;
  const n = b.length;
  // Flat 1D array avoids noUncheckedIndexedAccess warnings on 2D access
  const dp = new Int32Array((m + 1) * (n + 1));
  const idx = (i: number, j: number) => i * (n + 1) + j;
  for (let i = 0; i <= m; i++) dp[idx(i, 0)] = i;
  for (let j = 0; j <= n; j++) dp[idx(0, j)] = j;
  for (let i = 1; i <= m; i++) {
    for (let j = 1; j <= n; j++) {
      dp[idx(i, j)] =
        a[i - 1] === b[j - 1]
          ? dp[idx(i - 1, j - 1)]
          : 1 + Math.min(dp[idx(i - 1, j)], dp[idx(i, j - 1)], dp[idx(i - 1, j - 1)]);
    }
  }
  return dp[idx(m, n)];
};
```
`Int32Array` access never returns `undefined` (it returns 0 for out-of-bounds), so no `!` assertions are needed and Biome is happy. Alternatively, a `Uint32Array` or regular typed approach works too.

